    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Calculate the length of the curve \(y^2 = {@y^2@}\) between \(x = {@a@}\) and \(x = {@b@}\), in the first quadrant. Give your answer in <b>exact</b> form.</p>
<p>The length is [[input:ans1]]</p>
<p>[[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p> We are given \( y^2 = {@y^2@} \) then \( y = {@y@}\)on the first quadrant.</p>
<p> The derivative \( \dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} = {@dy@}.\)</p>

<p>Using the formula \[\text{length of curve}=\int_a^b \sqrt{1+\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\right)^2} \mathrm{d}x,\] the length of the line is calculated to be:
\[ \ell = \int_{{@a@}}^{{@b@}} \sqrt{1+{@dy^2@}} \, \mathrm{d}x = \left[ {@I@} \right]_{{@a@}}^{{@b@}} = {@ta1@}.\]</p>
<p>For this integral you can use the substitution \( u= 1+{@dy^2@}.\)</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
